NORMALISED EXTRACT

1. Definition and formal properties
- Hamming distance between two equal-length vectors/strings is the number of positions with differing symbols. For binary strings a and b of equal length, HammingDistance(a,b) = popcount(a XOR b).
- Metric properties: non-negativity, symmetry, identity of indiscernibles (distance 0 iff strings identical), triangle inequality.
- Complexity: computing Hamming distance by per-position comparison is O(n) time and O(1) extra space for strings of length n.

2. Binary implementation (integers)
- Convert two integers x and y into their bitwise exclusive-or v = x ^ y; the number of differing bit positions equals popcount(v).
- CPU/popcount options:
  - Use processor popcount instruction if available (x86 POPCNT) via compiler intrinsics: GCC/Clang: __builtin_popcount(unsigned int) for 32-bit, __builtin_popcountll(unsigned long long) for 64-bit.
  - Wegner method (loop clearing lowest set bit): while (v) { v = v & (v - 1); count++; } — costs O(popcount(v)) iterations.
  - Table lookup: precompute table for 16-bit values (array of size 65536) and do popcount32(x) = table[x & 0xFFFF] + table[x >> 16]. Memory vs speed trade-off: table of 65536 bytes yields fastest 32-bit counts with two table reads and addition.
  - Parallel add (divide-and-conquer masks) using constants m1,m2,m4,m8,m16,m32,h01 and 32/64-bit arithmetic to sum partial counts in log steps. Exact constants (for 64-bit): m1 = 0x5555555555555555; m2 = 0x3333333333333333; m4 = 0x0f0f0f0f0f0f0f0f; m8 = 0x00ff00ff00ff00ff; m16 = 0x0000ffff0000ffff; m32 = 0x00000000ffffffff; h01 = 0x0101010101010101.
- Example popcount reduction sequence (64-bit):
  1) x = (x & m1) + ((x >> 1) & m1)  -- counts per 2-bit fields
  2) x = (x & m2) + ((x >> 2) & m2)  -- counts per 4-bit fields
  3) x = (x & m4) + ((x >> 4) & m4)  -- counts per 8-bit fields
  4) x = (x + (x >> 8)) & m4         -- optional merge then multiply by h01 and shift to extract final sum
  5) final = (x * h01) >> 56  (returns total popcount for 64-bit using multiply-based method)
- C intrinsic signatures to rely on: int __builtin_popcount(unsigned int x); int __builtin_popcountll(unsigned long long x);

3. String implementation (Unicode-aware)
- For general strings: require equal-length sequences at the chosen unit of comparison. Hamming distance is defined only for equal-length sequences; otherwise, raise an error or pad/normalize beforehand.
- For Unicode text in JavaScript, iterate by Unicode code points not UTF-16 code units: using for...of or [...str] to obtain code points. Do not iterate by numeric indices because surrogate pairs will be visited twice and codePointAt may return surrogate code units when invoked on a trailing surrogate.
- MDN specifics: String.prototype.codePointAt(index) returns the Unicode code point starting at the given index; if the element at index is a UTF-16 leading surrogate, codePointAt returns the combined code point of the surrogate pair; if index points to a trailing surrogate, codePointAt returns only that trailing surrogate value. Safer approach: iterate with for...of and compare code points at each iteration via codePointAt(0) on the iterated element, or compare the iterated elements directly.
- Implementation variants:
  - Compare by code points: transform both strings into arrays of code points using [...str] and ensure equal lengths, then count mismatches between array elements.
  - Compare by encoded bytes: encode strings to a canonical byte encoding (UTF-8) and compare equal-length byte sequences. Note: must ensure both are normalized (NFC/NFD) if semantic equivalence is desired.

4. Popcount (Hamming weight) algorithms and constants
- Definitions: Hamming weight (popcount) is the number of 1 bits in a binary word. popcount(x) is the Hamming weight of x.
- Efficient algorithms provided:
  - Wegner (bit-clear) loop: while (x) { x &= x - 1; count++; }
  - Parallel summation (tree/HD): use masks m1,m2,m4,... and shifts and adds to aggregate counts in log2(word_size) steps. Masks/constants for 64-bit provided above.
  - multiply-accumulate variant: after reducing counts into bytes, multiply by h01 and shift to extract sum.
  - Lookup table variant: wordbits[0..65535] with wordbits[x] = popcount(x) for 16-bit blocks.
  - Vectorized and Harley–Seal algorithm: for platforms with SIMD, use vectorized popcount strategies; Harley–Seal offers fast integer-only approach.
- Complexity: Wegner loop is O(k) where k = popcount(x); divide-and-conquer and multiply methods are O(1) arithmetic operations independent of k (fixed number of operations) with worst-case cost smaller than per-bit loops.

5. Bitwise operator semantics (JavaScript)
- JavaScript bitwise operators treat operands as 32-bit signed integers (ToInt32 conversion). The result is also a 32-bit signed integer, converted back to Number. Therefore, for numbers outside 32-bit range, results are truncated to low 32 bits. Use >>>0 to coerce to unsigned 32-bit when needed.
- Operators: & (AND), | (OR), ^ (XOR), ~ (NOT), << (left shift), >> (signed right shift), >>> (unsigned right shift). XOR (^) is the operator used to identify differing bit positions between two 32-bit values.
- For Unicode and string Hamming operations in JS, rely on string-level iteration; do not use bitwise operators on string code unit values without acknowledging 16-bit truncation.
- MDN method notes: codePointAt(index) returns undefined if index out of bounds; when iterating by for...of, each iteration yields a string element that represents a Unicode code point; use element.codePointAt(0) to obtain numeric code point.

6. Performance and complexity
- Per-character string comparison: O(n) time, O(1) space; per-character cost includes character extraction and comparison (which may be more expensive for code point iteration).
- Integer XOR+popcount route: constant-time arithmetic instructions plus popcount; prefer processor popcount intrinsic for large-scale bit comparisons.
- Table-lookup vs arithmetic: lookup trades memory for fewer operations; on modern CPUs with hardware popcount, intrinsic is fastest; on SIMD-capable CPUs, vectorized popcount implementations may beat scalar intrinsics for large arrays.

7. Edge cases and failure modes
- Unequal-length inputs: Hamming distance undefined; choose policy: throw error, return sentinel, or normalize lengths before comparison.
- Strings with different Unicode normalizations: visually identical text may differ in code points; normalize with NFC/NFD before computing distance if desired.
- JavaScript numeric truncation: bitwise ops only work over 32-bit ranges; for >32-bit bitwise comparisons, use BigInt APIs or explicit byte-array handling.
- Surrogate handling: indexing strings by numeric index will split surrogate pairs; use for...of or [...str] when comparing by code point.

